SIMPLE: galvanism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Galvanism
<hw>Gal"va*nism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<ets>Galvani</ets>: cf. F. <ets>galvanisme</ets>. See
<er>Galvanic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>Electricity excited by the mutual action of certain liquids and
metals; dynamical electricity.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The branch of
physical science which treats of dynamical electricity, or the
properties and effects of electrical currents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The words <xex>galvanism</xex> and <xex>galvanic</xex>,
formerly in very general use, are now rarely employed. For the latter,
<xex>voltaic</xex>, from the name of <xex>Volta</xex>, is commonly
used.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Galvanist</ent>⟦br⟧
